  "prompt": "Why do cats spit hairballs? Is it harmful?",
  "response": "Cats spit hairballs because they groom themselves by licking their fur, which leads to ingested hair. Their tongues have tiny, hook-like structures that trap loose hair, and when the cat swallows this hair, it can accumulate in the stomach and form a hairball. Occasionally, hairballs are regurgitated to clear them from the digestive system.\n\nHairballs are generally not harmful to cats, but they can cause discomfort and occasional gagging or retching. In some cases, hairballs can lead to complications such as blockage in the digestive tract, which can be serious and might require veterinary intervention. Signs of such complications include frequent vomiting, lack of appetite, lethargy, and constipation.\n\nTo prevent hairballs, regular grooming can reduce the amount of loose hair that the cat ingests. Special diets, hairball remedies, and products designed to promote healthy digestion can also help. If your cat frequently experiences hairball issues, it\u2019s a good idea to consult a veterinarian for advice and possible treatment options.",
